By [JSON definition](https://www.json.org/json-en.html):
&gt;  JSON is built on two structures:&lt;br/&gt;
A collection of name/value pairs. In various languages, this is realized as an _object_, record, struct, dictionary, hash table, keyed list, or associative array.  
An ordered list of values. In most languages, this is realized as an _array_, vector, list, or sequence.
&gt;
&gt;An object is an **unordered** set of name/value pairs. 

Similarly, [`HashMap`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/HashMap.html) is not ordered either: _This class makes no guarantees as to the order of the map; in particular, it does not guarantee that the order will remain constant over time._

Next, the presented JSON is invalid and needs to be updated.

However, certain JSON libraries provide facilities to sort the fields for example, [`@JsonPropertyOrder`](https://www.baeldung.com/jackson-annotations) annotation in Jackson library.
